President Biden visited the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in Atlanta, Georgia, and expressed his gratitude to the agency for its work in fighting the COVID-19 pandemic. He acknowledged the early concerns raised by a mayor in Detroit about the disproportionate impact of the virus on African American communities and praised the CDC for its efforts in addressing this issue. The President emphasized the importance of science and the role it plays in guiding the country's response to public health crises. He commended the CDC for its dedication and expressed confidence that the agency's work will make the country healthier and better prepared for future crises. Vice President Harris also spoke, highlighting the administration's commitment to science and praising the CDC's global influence and dedication to improving public health. Both the President and Vice President thanked the CDC for its tireless work and emphasized the impact it has on saving lives and shaping the mindset of the country.